this orion design could not use pulse units that are much bigger then 20 to 30 kilotons in yield, Therefore maximium specific impulse is about 85000 seconds for this orion design.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=johndoe>John Doe</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 4<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(5/16/02 1:07:37 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=124.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://home.earthlink.net/~nsmessageboard/ezboard/posticons/fry1.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Orion Schematic</span><hr size=1> I don't understand one thing, does the orion drop an actual bomb into space for propulsion?<br>
<br>
Wouldn't it be easier to use an antimatter intiated micro  fission fusion?<br>
<br>
What you do is evelop a hydrogen core with an uranium shell. Then shoot an antiproton into the assembly.<br>
<br>
