<br>
Actually, it would be better to use the plasma from the reaction to propel the ship then to use the debree for thrust. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=cattlecar>cattlecar</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Cadet</span><br>  Posts: 47<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(5/16/02 4:53:36 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=124.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://home.earthlink.net/~nsmessageboard/ezboard/posticons/fry1.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Orion Schematic</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> <br>
I don't understand one thing, does the orion drop an actual bomb into space for propulsion?<br>
Wouldn't it be easier to use an antimatter intiated micro fission fusion?<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
An atomic bomb is detonated a 'classified' distance aft of the pusher<br>
plate.  Somewhere around 100-200 meters, depending on yield 'perhaps'.<br>
<br>
But it's not an ordinary A-Bomb.  Later in the original Project Orion,<br>
the scientists took to calling them 'Pulse Units'.<br>
<br>
Each Pulse Unit would contain a nuclear explosive device, and a<br>
propellant (polyethylene, later smaller pusher plates required a<br>
thinner slab of higher-density material, such as tungsten, to focus<br>
the bomb's energy into a narrower cone*) that is vaporized into plasma<br>
and directed toward the pusher plate providing a serious kick.<br>
<br>
These Pulse Units would have been fairly low yield, below 1 kiloton<br>
initially, with yields increasing with speed of the vehicle.<br>
<br>
A manned mission to Mars specified something on the order of 2000-3000<br>
pulse units.<br>
<br>
Would it be easier to use the anti-matter system you described? No.<br>
We can't store anit-matter very long, or create it in any usable<br>
quatities, yet.<br>
<br>
An Orion could be built using late 50's early 60's technology.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
